Seppuku

Target IP: 192.168.170.90

Scanning




Looks like there are eight TCP ports open on the target machine. There are multiple HTTP application for this machine.

Enumeration

Port 7601: HTTP


Running gobuster scan with the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.170.90:7601/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt -x html,txt,php --exclude-length 0 gives the result above. There is a lot of information.


Browsing to the /keys/ directory outputs two files as shown above.


The first file private contains SSH key of an unknown user. The second file private.bak contains a backup of the first file.


Another interesting directory I came across is the /secret/. The contents of this directory are shown above. The first file hostname contains the name seppuku. The password.lst contains a list of passwords.


The shadow.bak file contains a password hash of the user r@bbit-hole. Maybe we can use the password.lst to perform bruteforce against the hash found in shadow.bak?


After trying to crack the hash, I obtained the password a1b2c3. After spraying these credentials against the different logins, I had no luck. I will try to bruteforce the different services using the password.lst.


And finally I got a hit! This time I managed to obtain the credentials: seppuku:eeyoree.

Exploitation


Using the credentials from above, I managed to gain a foothold on the machine as seppuku.

Privilege Escalation


When looking for PE vectors, I notice we are in a restricted shell. To overcome this, I exited the SSH session, and started a new SSH session using the following command ssh seppuku@192.168.170.90 -t "bash --noprofile".


Earlier we found a SSH key called private. Maybe this SSH key belongs to one of the user?


After trying this, it worked! The SSH key belonged to a user called tanto.


There is a password file inside seppuku's home directory. Trying this password with the user samurai worked!



Creating the directory and shell file.

By using path abuse, I created a shell to replace the bin. Then I was able to call it to gain a root shell.

Flags


The local.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine.


The proof.txt flag once I exploited the path abuse weakness
